{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1930"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1930"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.79,0.06,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109490"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1930"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109490"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 31-year-old man presents with a one-day history of epigastric pain which becomes generalised and colicky in nature. His abdomen is slightly distended and soft to palpation. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed. (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/images/8e0d85f2-3a30-410e-9bac-440088e00a88.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following descriptions best fits the radiological appearances?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal pattern","Pneumoperitoneum","Small bowel obstruction","Large bowel obstruction","Pneumatosis coli"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a healthy person, only a small volume of gas will be visible within the small bowel. In this case, most of the small bowel is displayed with a large volume of gas. An abdominal X-ray is often the first-line imaging investigation performed for suspected bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe 3-6-9 rule provides guidelines for normal widths of different parts of the gastrointestinal tract on abdominal X-ray:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esmall intestines should be less than 3cm,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elarge intestine should be less than 6cm,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecaecum should be less than 9cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProminent plicae circulares are seen within the bowel loops in the image, which characterises the small bowel. Since the bowel loops are greater than 3cm in width and are located centrally within the abdomen, there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter reaching this diagnosis, it is advisable to perform cross-sectional imaging CT with intravenous contrast, as to determine a transition point and assess for potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E often occurs secondary to colon cancer or volvulus. On an abdominal X-ray, this is seen as bowel loops dilated, with loop widths described above, proximal to the obstruction, with presence of haustra and absence of pliacae circularis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumatosis coli \u003C/strong\u003Eis the presence of gas within the intestinal wall, and is often associated with intestinal ischaemia or colitis in the adult population and necrotising enterocolitis in premature neonates. There is no evidence of intramural gas in the radiograph, so this is an unlikely option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumoperitoneum \u003C/strong\u003Edescribes the abnormal presence of air within the peritoneal cavity. This is a consequence of bowel perforation and can be usually visualised as air trapping under the diaphragm in an erect chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A small bowel obstruction is seen on abdominal X-ray as dilated bowl loops greater than 3cm in width, with plicae circulares visible."],"references":["Nelms DW, Kann BR. Imaging Modalities for Evaluation of Intestinal Obstruction. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021 Jun 2; 34(4): 205\u2013218. doi: 10.1055/s-0041-1729737"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1930"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20122"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20122"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e0d85f2-3a30-410e-9bac-440088e00a88.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e0d85f2-3a30-410e-9bac-440088e00a88.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T20:24:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T20:24:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1930"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109490"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-1